          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Glycogen used &darr; Fatty acid used &uarr; Oxygen consumed &uarr;</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">During a marathon, a runner heavily relies on stored energy sources and oxygen. Considering the metabolic changes that occur over the course of a marathon, which option best describes the changes in glycogen and fatty acid utilization, as well as oxygen consumption, comparing the first mile to the 26th mile?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q9364652",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 29982,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. D) Decreased glycogen used, increased fatty acids and oxygen consumed</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">During <strong>prolonged exercise</strong> such as a <strong>marathon,</strong> the body initially relies on<strong> glycogen stores for energy</strong>. However, as the <strong>race</strong> <strong>progresses,</strong> <strong>glycogen stores</strong> become <strong>depleted</strong>, and the <strong>body increasingly</strong> turns to<strong> fatty acids for fuel.</strong> This shift is known as the &quot;<strong>crossover&quot;</strong> effect and is a result of<strong> increased enzyme activity </strong>related to <strong>fat metabolism</strong> as the duration of <strong>exercise increases</strong>. Moreover, <strong>oxygen </strong>consumption remains<strong> high </strong>throughout the<strong> race to meet the aerobic demands </strong>of <strong>prolonged exercise, </strong>facilitating both<strong> glycogen and fatty acid metabolism.</strong> Therefore, by the <strong>end of a marathon</strong>, the utilization of<strong> glycogen decreases </strong>due to <strong>depletion of stores,</strong> <strong>fatty acid</strong> utilization <strong>increases</strong> as the <strong>primary energy source, </strong>and <strong>oxygen </strong>consumption remains <strong>elevated to</strong> support<strong> aerobic metabolism.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Other Options:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. Increased glycogen used, increased fatty acids used, increased oxygen consumed:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> This option is<strong> incorrect</strong> because, while <strong>oxygen</strong> consumption does<strong> increase</strong>, <strong>glycogen</strong> utilization<strong> decreases </strong>over time due to <strong>depletion of stores.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B. Increased glycogen used, decreased fatty acids used, decreased oxygen consumed:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> This option<strong> does not</strong> reflect the <strong>metabolic shift to increased fatty acid</strong> utilization and the sustained<strong> high oxygen consumption</strong> in <strong>prolonged exercise.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. Increased glycogen used, decreased fatty acids used, increased oxygen consumed:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> This option also<strong> fails </strong>to account for the shift towards <strong>greater fatty acid utilization </strong>as<strong> glycogen stores </strong>are <strong>depleted.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">At the <strong>beginning </strong>of the<strong> race, </strong>a <strong>runner </strong>consumes<strong> energy</strong> at a ratio of <strong>75 percent carbohydrate</strong>: <strong>25 percent fatty acids</strong> approximately. </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">By the <strong>end of the race</strong>, glycogen stores are mostly<strong> depleted</strong> and the generation of <strong>ATPs from Beta-oxidation of fatty acids</strong> occurs &rarr; produces <strong>reducing equivalents </strong>for<strong> oxidative phosphorylation. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">This requires an<strong> increase </strong>in the amount of<strong> oxygen consumed.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Harper 30/e: p 663.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
