          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">It liberates heat by coupling oxidation from phosphorylation</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Which of the following statements is true regarding the specialized mammalian tissue/organ where fuel oxidation is primarily used to generate heat rather than produce ATP?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q8678592",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 29984,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. B) Non-shivering thermogenesis is a hormonal stimulus </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Brown adipose tissue</strong> contains <strong>thermogenin</strong>, which is a<strong> physiological uncoupler </strong>of <strong>oxidative phosphorylation</strong>. This process is called <strong>Non-shivering Thermogenesis.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Non-shivering thermogenesis </strong>is a <strong>hormonal stimulus </strong>for <strong>heat generation without </strong>the associated <strong>muscle contractions </strong>of shivering.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. It is concerned with energy storage:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> This statement is <strong>more applicable </strong>to <strong>white adipose tissue</strong>, which is the <strong>body&#39;s main form of energy storage. Brown adipose tissue</strong>, on the other hand, is specialized for<strong> energy expenditure </strong>in the form of<strong> heat</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. It is primarily important in adults:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>Brown adipose tissue </strong>is most <strong>prominent and active in infants</strong>, where it plays a critical role in <strong>thermogenesis </strong>to maintain <strong>body temperature</strong>. Its <strong>prevalence and activity </strong>typically <strong>decrease with age</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D. It liberates heat by coupling oxidation from phosphorylation:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> The<strong> correct </strong>mechanism in<strong> brown adipose tissue </strong>involves the <strong>uncoupling of oxidation </strong>from <strong>phosphorylation</strong>, <strong>not coupling</strong>, which allows the <strong>energy from fuel oxidation</strong> to be <strong>released as heat</strong> instead of being used to produce ATP.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Brown adipose tissue (BAT)</strong> is primarily involved in<strong> non-shivering thermogenesis, </strong>a process of<strong> heat production in mammals</strong>. This process is <strong>stimulated hormonally, </strong>particularly by<strong> norepinephrine</strong>, which is released in response to <strong>cold exposure. BAT </strong>contains a <strong>high number of mitochondria </strong>with <strong>uncoupling protein 1 </strong>(UCP1), which allows the <strong>uncoupling of oxidative phosphorylation; instead</strong> of <strong>producing ATP</strong>, the<strong> energy </strong>is released as <strong>heat</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Harper 30/e: p 132,264, Vasudevan 9/e: p 162,266.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
