      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A lean patient with a pre-existing medical condition is being maintained on a diet composed exclusively of carbohydrates. What would be the Respiratory Quotient (RQ) of this patient?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q2980104",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 29980,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. C) 1</span></strong> </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C: </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Respiratory quotient (RQ)</strong> is the<strong> ratio </strong>of volume of <strong>CO2<strong> </strong>produced</strong> in <strong>L/g</strong> to the <strong>oxygen consumed </strong>in <strong>L/g.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>RQ </strong>of <strong>carbohydrates</strong> = <strong>1</strong> &amp; <strong>fats = 0.7 &amp; proteins = 0.8 </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">For a <strong>mixed diet </strong>it is between <strong>0.7 and 1</strong>(around 0.82&ndash;0.85)</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">When the <strong>rate of utilization</strong> of <strong>fat increases</strong> in relation to <strong>carbohydrates</strong> and the <strong>RQ falls,</strong> which is <strong>seen</strong> in<strong> diabetes</strong> <strong>mellitus</strong>, when <strong>utilization of carbohydrate</strong> is <strong>reduced</strong>. And it is<strong> lowest </strong>when<strong> ketolysis</strong> is<strong> very active.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>Other Options:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A. 0.7:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong> RQ </strong>of <strong>fats = 0.7 </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B. 0.8:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> <strong>RQ</strong> of <strong>proteins </strong>= <strong>0.8 </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D. 0.93:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> <strong>RQ </strong>of mixed diet it is between<strong> 0.7 and 1</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The <strong>Respiratory Quotient (RQ) </strong>is a measure of the <strong>ratio of carbon dioxide</strong> <strong>produced</strong> to<strong> oxygen consumed</strong>. An <strong>RQ of 1 </strong>is typically <strong>indicative</strong> of <strong>carbohydrate metabolism</strong>, as <strong>carbohydrates </strong>are completely<strong> oxidized to</strong> <strong>carbon dioxide and water.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Harper 30/e:&nbsp; p 541.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
