      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Regarding Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR), which of the following statements is accurate?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q1191018",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 29981,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. B) Decreases in response to starvation</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Explanation:</strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">BMR decreases in response to starvation as a physiological adaptation to conserve energy. When food intake is significantly reduced, the body lowers its metabolic rate to decrease energy expenditure, helping to prolong survival during periods of food scarcity.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation</u></strong>:</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option A. Increases in response to starvation</strong>: This is incorrect; the body decreases metabolic rate in response to starvation to conserve energy.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C. Is not responsive to changes in hormone levels</strong>: This is incorrect; BMR is influenced by various hormones, including thyroid hormones, which can increase metabolic rate, and cortisol, which can have complex effects on metabolism.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D. Increases with increasing age</strong>: This is generally incorrect; BMR tends to decrease with age due to factors such as reduced muscle mass and changes in body composition.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Factors Affecting BMR</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Age</strong>: BMR is high during active growth and reaches a maximum by 5 years of age. In old age BMR is lowered.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Sex</strong>: Males have a higher BMR than females.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Temperature</strong>: BMR increases in cold climates as a compensatory mechanism to maintain body temperature. E.g. Eskimos.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Exercise</strong>: BMR increases during exercise due to increased cardiac output and Starvation lowers BMR.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Fever</strong>: About 12% increase in BMR per degree centigrade rise in temperature.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Thyroid hormones</strong>: They have a general stimulant effect on rate of metabolism and heat production, BMR is raised in hyperthyroidism and lowered in hypothyroidism.&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ref</strong>: DM Vasudevan 9/e: p 528.</span></p>",
